Locality: Stakeout—Merlin nest—Bedford Rd, Upper Arlington US-OH (39.9973,-83.0568)
Observation Details: Nestwatch; FIVE recently fledged young, approximately 26-30 days old. Upon arrival at 8:00 they were dispersed and tough to find in the dense canopy of ginkgo and maple. We could find what I assumed were the three young I had barely seen the heads of in the nest a week ago. It was pretty quiet until 9:00 when adults brought in food, and suddenly there were FOUR lined up on one limb! The FIFTH and presumed youngest was still by the nest but watching his nestmates closely and is close to being able to make the leap from the ginkgo to the maple. We watched the female bring in two birds and saw two fledglings pluck prey and eat. The young birds seemed content to wait their turn and never crowded the feeding bird. A lot of down was sifting out as the juvenile birds preened. We had a scope set up and showed the birds to neighbors and kids passing by.

Locality: USDA, Appalachian Fruit Research Station, Bardane
Observation Details: Initially seen perched on some wild grape vines growing into a cluster of trees. An American Crow did not accept the Merlin's presence, and chased it from that perch to a perch in one of the apple tree blocks. I feel fortunate to have been able to get photos of both upper and lower body.

Perched north of playground, eating male House Sparrow. The coloration looked different than those I've observed lately. Kimball kindly provided feedback on this interesting individual, "I agree with you that this looks a bit darker than a typical richardsoni. On the other hand, it is certainly at the pale end for columbarius (which is a highly variable subspecies, spanning almost the continuum of phenotypes from dark extreme richardsoni to pale-extreme suckleyi.  Factoring in also the intergradation that occurs at subspecies boundaries, and I wonder if it is wise to put a subspecies name on this bird.  Both richardsoni and columbarius have expanded their breeding ranges in recent decades, and I suspect that intergradation is frequent."

Observation Details: Rare winter bird on MDI.  Immature  found along Knox Road. Initially on telephone wire then a truck disturbed it to a tree. Yellow cere, commisure and eye-ring offset beautifully the white supraorbital ridge, supercillium, malar and belly. Upperparts are streaked with white spotting on the flanks. The tail is banded white and brown with a distinctive broad white band on the tip. Pointed checkered underwings.

One Merlin landed on the cut top of a tree with a House Finch it just caught. I watched for 10 minutes as he was taking the feathers off the bird and starting to eat a bit of it until two American Crows joined the feast and the Merlin left with his prey. It was fascinating to see that first it held the bird long enough to make sure it was dead (first photo). Then, it removed a few feathers around the neck (photo 2 ) and ate too pieces, one red and one whitish (photo 3). Then , it started to pluck the bird, first the the tail feathers and then the wings primary feathers. It quickly plucked more smaller feathers. It did it  super fast while stopping from time to  time to evaluate the threat of its surroundings. (photo 4).  It turned the House Finch around, probably to continue this job (photo 5), when a couple of American Crows appeared . The Merlin quickly grabbed its prey and flew to a different tree. the crows stayed a while trying to glean any little pieces they could, I doubt they found much.

Observation Details: Initially seen in a medium-sized tree along Elmwood just north of the parking lot. After about 15 minutes I saw it fly off to the northeast from atop the siren. About 7-8 minutes after that it flew back into a second tree on Elmwood, a bit closer to the tennis courts. As I was photographing it, a Cooper's Hawk flew in over the tennis courts and made a pass at the Merlin, then continued to the northwest. The Merlin ducked, sat for about 3-4 seconds longer, then flew off to the northwest after the Cooper's Hawk.

*Good looks and photos- Subspecies ID mainly based on coloration, clearly intermediate between the other two North American types.  Prairie would be much paler overall, almost a light gray.  Pacific/Black would be much darker on both the back and the breast.  Coloration is typical of Taiga, with slate blue/gray back and wings. It also lacks the dark mottling the undersides that Pacific birds show. Another field mark that clinches the ID of Taiga is the fact that the primaries are dark, but contrast a bit with a slightly lighter back color.  On a Pacific ssp, the back would be equally dark as the primaries, lacking the contrast of Taiga Merlin.  Also note sparsely marked undertail coverts.

Locality: Sevenmile Creek--Prickly Pear Land Trust (restricted access)
Observation Details: Flew in from the S or SE at 1621 and perched 1 m high on a dead wood branch in the new section of reach 3 at the stream edge. Observed until 1626 - perched quietly, looked around, and groomed foot a bit. Gone at 1626. At 1633, the MERL reappeared perched in a planted Salix ca 20 m E of the wooden board spanning the stream. At 1641, it glided down from the 1.5 m high perch to the creek vicinity and disappeared, out of sight. At 1643, a BBMA perched near the bank of the stream nearby and made occasional calls, then flew off as I got within ca 40 m. At 1647, the MERL reappeared, flying up (to the Salix) without prey from the stream near the plank bridge - had it been bathing, or drinking, or hunting? It seemed to struggle with balance a bit - flicked wings open several times and spread tail. The final photo I got on this perch was of takeoff. At 1649, it flew WNW to perch in the top of an Alnus incana near one of the ponds. at 1653, it flew on upstream after 5 AMCR flew by, also heading upstream. It closed the distance between it and them, then dove (whether on a crow or something else, I couldn't tell). This was my last sighting of it on this day.

Observation Details: Brown back indicates female or imm of either sex, combined with small apparent size in field, suggests imm male (I initially mistook it for a female AMKE). Apparently a  "Prairie" Merlin, F. c. Richardsonii, or near so intergrade. Light to intermediate brown back color, prominent supercilium that projects strongly to rear of crown, and plain face without dark and obvious vertical lacrymal and auricular bars also supports "Prairie" Merlin. Additionally, the light buff spots just visible in outer primaries, very fine streaks on tibials, and unmarked undertail coverts further suggests a"Prairie" Merlin. Underside of outermost rectrices show at least 5 pale horizontal bars. Comments welcome. Added 3/20/2022: outside expert opinion consider this a "tweener" citing upperparts a a shade too dark for "pure" Richardsonii, with one suggesting it represents the intermediate "Bendire's" form that is no longer considered a valid subspecies by contemporary ornithologist.

Flew by me with prey landing on an old utility pole. Observation Details: ***MEGA subspecies - probably a first NY record; this very dark Merlin was perched atop a utility pole south of Aurora. I saw it naked eye as we were driving past, and did a quick u-turn because it appeared to be all dark. I took some photos of the bird as it perched and then flew; these revealed the general lack of pale spotting/ barring on the remiges, which are very important to the subspecific identification:  http://elibrary.unm.edu/sora/Auk/v089n02/p0325-p0338.pdf). Most Taiga Merlins show extensive pale barring throughout the remiges, a feature notably lacking on this bird. The dark "helmet" and underparts were also very dark, much moreso than typical Taiga birds.

Media notes: Eating a prey. Date added to IBC: October 28, 2017.

Observation Details: One Merlin landed on the cut top of a tree with a House Finch it just caught. I watched for 10 minutes as he was taking the feathers off the bird and starting to eat a bit of it until two American Crows joined the feast and the Merlin left with his prey. It was fascinating to see that first it held the bird long enough to make sure it was dead (first photo). Then, it removed a few feathers around the neck (photo 2 ) and ate too pieces, one red and one whitish (photo 3). Then , it started to pluck the bird, first the the tail feathers and then the wings primary feathers. It quickly plucked more smaller feathers. It did it  super fast while stopping from time to  time to evaluate the threat of its surroundings. (photo 4).  It turned the House Finch around, probably to continue this job (photo 5), when a couple of American Crows appeared . The Merlin quickly grabbed its prey and flew to a different tree. the crows stayed a while trying to glean any little pieces they could, I doubt they found much.

Spotted in top of snag behind the tattoo shop on 1300 S, 4 blocks from Liberty Park. Appeared  to be the Black subspecies bird Bryant has been reporting at the park. Jeanne and Ray drove by and we observed it eat what looked like a European Starling.

Perched north of playground, eating male House Sparrow. The coloration looked different than those I've observed lately. Kimball kindly provided feedback on this interesting individual, "I agree with you that this looks a bit darker than a typical richardsoni. On the other hand, it is certainly at the pale end for columbarius (which is a highly variable subspecies, spanning almost the continuum of phenotypes from dark extreme richardsoni to pale-extreme suckleyi.  Factoring in also the intergradation that occurs at subspecies boundaries, and I wonder if it is wise to put a subspecies name on this bird.  Both richardsoni and columbarius have expanded their breeding ranges in recent decades, and I suspect that intergradation is frequent."

From its perch overlooking the HK south pond, the Merlin was a focused hunter. It would occasionally launch into the air fly out over the ponds, intercept a dragonfly, and then return to its perch to consume its catch. During one of these hunting sessions, an Anna’s Hummingbird made a feeble attempt to challenge the Merlin but quickly decided to pursue other safer hummingbird activities.

Observation Details: Same general area as last year. Thought there might be two but can confirm only one. Heard it calling and have a couple of distant photos.

When I arrived, one bird was perched out in the open and by about 6:30 all the flying and vocalizing ceased and no Merlins were seen until 7:07, not even on the power stanchion where one perched for quite a long time last evening.  Activity picked up again and at 7:35 I realized that the third bird that I hadn't seen was perched in a tree, after one of the other birds flew over towards it calling and chased it off its perch. Later two birds flew right past me while one was perched, and one of the birds in flight had caught a bird. I am 99% sure that I know what tree the nest may be in, which is not within the cemetery, it's very large and dense and I just cannot see anything resembling a nest. There's only one active bird this evening and I'm pretty sure it's the male who perches nearby and then flies around calling, and repeats. It might leave the area and then, when it flies back in, it seems to either circle that tree once or make a very close pass at that tree. Sometimes a bird perches in a tree next to the tree I think the nest is in, which is nowhere near their winter roosting trees. This is exceptionally frustrating, because I thought we were friends. I was going to use the breeding code for Visiting Probable Nest Site because of their attraction to that tree, but I can't say that I saw them perch in it. I don't think that the one bird chasing the third bird was necessarily territorial defense, since they mess with each other like that through the winter, too. I thought the female might have been on the nest because the one bird would fly around that tree and vocalize, but later I saw two birds out perched, so I just can't keep up with them.  I'm sure that missing this window of time in April and not realizing that they would disappear earlier in the evening is why I have missed what probably were prior successful nestings. When I would drive through and not see them, I assume they had left, and I stopped visiting regularly through the rest of the spring and summer.

Brown back indicates female or imm of either sex, combined with small apparent size in field, suggests imm male (I initially mistook it for a female AMKE). Apparently a  "Prairie" Merlin, F. c. Richardsonii, or near so intergrade. Light to intermediate brown back color, prominent supercilium that projects strongly to rear of crown, and plain face without dark and obvious vertical lacrymal and auricular bars also supports "Prairie" Merlin. Additionally, the light buff spots just visible in outer primaries, very fine streaks on tibials, and unmarked undertail coverts further suggests a"Prairie" Merlin. Underside of outermost rectrices show at least 5 pale horizontal bars. Comments welcome. Added 3/20/2022: outside expert opinion consider this a "tweener" citing upperparts a a shade too dark for "pure" Richardsonii, with one suggesting it represents the intermediate "Bendire's" form that is no longer considered a valid subspecies by contemporary ornithologist.

I heard one vocalizing and saw it flying in circles over a tree. It called a couple more times and then it flew towards the southwest, meandering a little, circling a little and then continuing on. Very shortly thereafter, one landed on a power stanchion and there's no way it could have been the same bird because the bird flying towards the southwest absolutely could not have turned and come back that far, that fast. Later as I was photographing the one perched on the stanchion, the second one came back and they both actually had a little interaction right above me as I was standing there with my mouth hanging open. The recording of a brief vocalization from that is attached to this report. First time for 2 in June; second consecutive year for Summit County Summer Breeding Bird Census.

Adult pair and two chicks in nest located in the courtyard of the library in the top of a spruce tree. When I first arrived the female was extremely vocal while perched in a snag across the street, but she soon quieted down and preened for about an hour before taking off. She stayed pretty close, but didn’t visit the nest until about 12:50pm. While the female was perched across the street, the male flew in about 12:40pm calling but perched on the branch beside the nest rather than going directly to it. He then flew off towards the female, presumably exchanging the prey item, which appeared to be a House Sparrow. She waited a few minutes before bringing it to the nest but immediately began feeding the chicks upon arrival. She flew across the street after about 5 minutes and began eating some of the prey for herself. She returned to the nest again at 1:10pm and fed the chicks for another 2 minutes before returning to her favored perch across the street. Have photos and videos.

4:06 PM, I discovered 2 Merlins in close proximity to one another in adjacent trees.  Then one flew into the same tree as the other.  I stayed with them for a few minutes and took a couple pictures.  Moving on, i walked away from them and at 4:14 PM I noticed another Merlin perched on a much shorter tree, only about 18 feet off the ground.  I was shocked at the prospect of 3 merlins, as i had routinely seen 2 here over the past 2 years.  Wondering if it was possible for one of the previous 2 i had just seen to make a very quick circuitous route to this tree that was about 100 yards away from where I had just seen the other 2.  But I had not seen any of them leave the tree.  Nor any flight movement above me.  It was a 3rd Merlin.  Which was a pretty sweet development.

Il attrape une tourterelle à nos mangeoires. Au bout de 10 minutes, il abandonne sa proie dans le fond de la cour et vient se poser sur le bord du bain chauffant juste en face de nous! Ensuite, il revient à sa proie. Un peu plus  tard, trois corneilles arrivent dans un érable et une douzaine de pigeons se posent tout près du faucon et mangent sans s'occuper de lui. Après être resté de longues minutes à surveiller corneilles et pigeons sans bouger, il recommence à manger et finit par s'envoler avec ce qu'il reste de la tourterelle pour s'engouffrer dans un grand conifère chez le quatrième voisin.

Vers 11h10, une cacophonie de cris d’oiseaux se fait entendre dans la cour arrière. Claire regarde par la fenêtre et découvre rapidement la cause de tout ce vacarme. Un Faucon émerillon est posé sur les branches d’une grande épinette et dévore une proie, pour le moment inconnue. Non loin de lui, un Merle d’Amérique crie au meurtre, peu de temps après un Quiscale bronzé ainsi que des étourneaux viennent jeter un coup d’œil eux aussi. Cette agitation n’est pas sans déranger le repas du faucon, qui de temps en temps, jette un coup d’œil dans les environs. Sûrement agacé par cette agitation le faucon prend sa proie (un étourneau) et s’envole pour disparaître définitivement.

Sitting on power pole on Badger Pocket Road across from the feedlot where the peregrine has been the last couple of months. A prairie (richardsonii)   female on power pole usually occupied by the peregrine. Thanks to Brian Pendleton who I ran into later--he asked me if it was male or female. I had a "duh" moment but checked my books and see that it clearly is a female with no gray/blue on her back. Thanks Brian, I learn something every time I meet another birder!!

One Merlin landed on the cut top of a tree with a House Finch it just caught. I watched for 10 minutes as he was taking the feathers off the bird and starting to eat a bit of it until two American Crows joined the feast and the Merlin left with his prey. It was fascinating to see that first it held the bird long enough to make sure it was dead (first photo). Then, it removed a few feathers around the neck (photo 2 ) and ate too pieces, one red and one whitish (photo 3). Then , it started to pluck the bird, first the the tail feathers and then the wings primary feathers. It quickly plucked more smaller feathers. It did it  super fast while stopping from time to  time to evaluate the threat of its surroundings. (photo 4).  It turned the House Finch around, probably to continue this job (photo 5), when a couple of American Crows appeared . The Merlin quickly grabbed its prey and flew to a different tree. the crows stayed a while trying to glean any little pieces they could, I doubt they found much.

*Good looks and photos- Subspecies ID mainly based on coloration, clearly intermediate between the other two North American types.  Prairie would be much paler overall, almost a light gray.  Pacific/Black would be much darker on both the back and the breast.  Coloration is typical of Taiga, with slate blue/gray back and wings. It also lacks the dark mottling the undersides that Pacific birds show. Another field mark that clinches the ID of Taiga is the fact that the primaries are dark, but contrast a bit with a slightly lighter back color.  On a Pacific ssp, the back would be equally dark as the primaries, lacking the contrast of Taiga Merlin.  Also note sparsely marked undertail coverts.
Considered Prairie Merlin, but cheek line seems dark, and overall perhaps not pallid enough?

***MEGA subspecies, following two days of strong westerlies which continued today. Sitting on the chimney across the street. Much darker than the Taiga subspecies that is usual here; very black both dorsally and on the breast. It preened and sat for quite a while, then flew off. Unfortunately I didn't manage a flight shot. Tail had three indistinct bands, unlike the more pronounced bands on F.c.c. The presence of white spots on the breast feathers is consistent with suckleyi, and I expect they would be absent or at least less pronounced on a truly melanistic example of the usual subspecies. Open to other identification interpretations, including the possibility that this is a F.c.c (melanistic) bird, but after comparing many photos, and examining specimens at the Museum of Comparative Zoology, Harvard University, I conclude this is most likely a Pacific ssp. Other photos exist, though all look much like these; no spread wing or tail shots could be obtained.

Adult female columbarius.  I.D. Points: Notice the the dark eyes, weak mustache (malar) gray back (with darker gray adult feathers growing in) brown flanks with white spots (not very diagnostic in this photo) Not often visible in the field, the darker centers of the wing coverts near the shoulder can be seen well here. Also a tough field mark- the uppertail coverts are darker gray, matching the new adult back feathers which can be used accurately to age most female merlins in the hand or in some photos. The darker subterminal band at the end of the tail also indicates this is an adult bird

Locality: Cayuga Co.--90 (Lake Rd to Ledyard Rd)
Observation Details: ***MEGA subspecies - probably a first NY record; this very dark Merlin was perched atop a utility pole south of Aurora. I saw it naked eye as we were driving past, and did a quick u-turn because it appeared to be all dark. I took some photos of the bird as it perched and then flew; these revealed the general lack of pale spotting/ barring on the remiges, which are very important to the subspecific identification:  http://elibrary.unm.edu/sora/Auk/v089n02/p0325-p0338.pdf). Most Taiga Merlins show extensive pale barring throughout the remiges, a feature notably lacking on this bird. The dark "helmet" and underparts were also very dark, much moreso than typical Taiga birds.

Flew in from the N at ca 1733 (seen before starting this count, while walking home from work along Breckenridge St). Thought it perhaps had a full crop. At that point I could tell it was a Falco, but did not get a sense of size. Spotted again at the beginning of this count, at which point it was perched in a Black Walnut E of Hoback, S of Broadway, looking around. Could not quite tell in the field whether it was a male or female/imm based on back color (back was to the NE), but photos confirm that the back is light grayish, indicating adult male. Remained in the Black Walnut until 1755, when it flew to the S or SE. Soon spotted it again (with help from a neighbor) in the top of a spruce along the alley between Hoback and Alta, ca 50 m SE of its previous perch. Neighbors saw a male Prairie Merlin perched W of Hoback sometime between 0700 and 0800 on the morning of the same day.

Small Falcon with weak "mustache" and light plumage on face which makes me believe this could be a "Prairie" Merlin.   The last photo with an entrail in the mouth seems to show white undertail coverts, which also would be a "Prairie."  Other photos seem to show darker gray wings and the breast striping seems heavy, so perhaps a "Taiga" Merlin.   Legs are covered with tawny plumage, which I have seen on both "Prairie" and "Taiga" in photos in books and online.

Merlin#1:  A Northern Flicker stopped in the middle of the gravel road in front of my car.  I pulled my binoculars to my eyes and stopped to watch it. I heard then saw a small falcon flying across the front of my car.  It hit the woodpecker with its talons.  The woodpecker sat there and the falcon hit it again.. but the woodpecker appeared to recover -  and flew off.  The Merlin flew up onto the top of a small cottonwood and perched for a minute- until the Merlin noticed an immature Bald Eagle perched in a cottonwood 20 yards away.  The Merlin flew off (followed by the eagle) and landed in another cottonwood (occupied by a black billed magpie).   The magpie harassed the Merlin - and the the Bald Eagle took off after the Merlin.  The Merlin flushed and flew after three Western Meadowlarks.  I lost sight of them in a recently harvested field.   I sat in the car for about 5 minutes and looked for the magpie which had started vocalizing again.  Then I spotted the eagle, magpie and Merlin again in a tree row about 50 yards away.  After about 15 minutes, I left them.       Merlin #2 sighting was unexpected.  It sitting in a small dead tree overlooking a ditch approximately a mile from the first sighting (5 minutes after I left Merlin #1).  Merlin # 2 was sitting on a branch in a dead tree about 3-feet from another branch (on the same dead tree) where a kestrel was perched. (I didn't see the Merlin sitting there at first).  I crept up (in my car) to take a photo of the kestrel but it flew off, revealing the Merlin (who sat for a photo).

Merlin#1:  A Northern Flicker stopped in the middle of the gravel road in front of my car.  I pulled my binoculars to my eyes and stopped to watch it. I heard then saw a small falcon flying across the front of my car.  It hit the woodpecker with its talons. Observation Details: I was about to give up on chances of a nest this year based on the dwindling numbers of Merlins I've been seeing, but this evening I observed one flying around an evergreen tree a couple of times where it chased off a crow, and the Merlin was vocalizing, and I found a nest in the top of the tree and it certainly looked like the Merlin is interested in claiming it.  It's early for them to nest, but this is also around the time when most of them start leaving the area. Three birds "may" be breeding pair and 1st year male... After I located the three, it was too dark to tell.

Il a attrapé un étourneau sansonnet et l'a tué et mangé devant nous sur le patio. De temps en temps le faucon regardait derrière lui parce qu'il y avait des corneilles qui s'étaient approchées et il les surveillait. Pendant presque 30secs, le faucon s'est écrasé complètement sur sa proie, les ailes fermées et il ne bougeait plus. Nous avons réalisé trop tard qu'un épervier brun était perché dans les érables derrière la maison et surveillait une mésange à tête noire; qu'il a raté d'ailleurs. Locality: Sevenmile Creek--Prickly Pear Land Trust (restricted access)
Observation Details: Flew in from the S or SE at 1621 and perched 1 m high on a dead wood branch in the new section of reach 3 at the stream edge. Observed until 1626 - perched quietly, looked around, and groomed foot a bit. Gone at 1626. At 1633, the MERL reappeared perched in a planted Salix ca 20 m E of the wooden board spanning the stream. At 1641, it glided down from the 1.5 m high perch to the creek vicinity and disappeared, out of sight. At 1643, a BBMA perched near the bank of the stream nearby and made occasional calls, then flew off as I got within ca 40 m. At 1647, the MERL reappeared, flying up (to the Salix) without prey from the stream near the plank bridge - had it been bathing, or drinking, or hunting? It seemed to struggle with balance a bit - flicked wings open several times and spread tail. The final photo I got on this perch was of takeoff. At 1649, it flew WNW to perch in the top of an Alnus incana near one of the ponds. at 1653, it flew on upstream after 5 AMCR flew by, also heading upstream. It closed the distance between it and them, then dove (whether on a crow or something else, I couldn't tell). This was my last sighting of it on this day.

Locality: HWY 10/10A Flin Flon Campground Marsh &  Mud Lake

Observation Details: Two birds were hanging around the white pine stand adjacent to the main parking lot. One bird remained hidden in the highest part of a white pine giving short "kip" contact call to the other visible bird who gave the standard Merlin call. The birds were there when we arrived, and still vocalizing to one another when we left hours later. I suspect that this may be a pair and possibly breeding in this grove. Further observations needed to confirm or deny, but Merlin is a species whose breeding range continues to push south, and has bred in the southern tier of New York and northeastern PA.

Chickadees gave their high-pitched alarm call - the Merlin flew in from the east and perched on a  pole near the Fairgrounds entrance for a few minutes before flying NE - I think because I got too close to it (ca 20 m).  It flew to the top of a spruce, distant NE of the pond.  Looking at the pictures I got, I think it's clearly a Prairie Merlin - pale edging on upperwing coverts and scapulars (and also on tertials); buffy spotting in upperwing coverts and flight feathers; pale auriculars; sandy brown coloration above; and 4 whitish tail bands dorsally (excluding the terminal band).

Saw it perched on a light standard so pulled over to double-check. It flew down into bushes and zipped out and after a small bird in flight. It then shifted course and came and perched in a low branch of the tree right across from me. It then proceeded to tear apart its prey. All of the feathers it was pulling off were gray and a Black-capped Chickadee was protesting nearby so I assumed it was a chickadee. However when it lifted it up at one point, it was a House Finch. Maybe there were two birds ... ???

Media notes: Tomial tooth (triangular-shaped ridge on the outer edge of the upper mandible) is visible in this photo. Primarily used to kill by biting the necks and severing vertebrae and spinal cord to dispatch their prey. This adaptation is often matched by a mandibular notch or divot in the lower mandible, that is most often found in falcons, kites, accipiters and other birds such as shrikes that primarily prey on birds.

First seen at 1301 very soon after the SSHA flew out of sight.The MERL flew in from ca east and landed in the top of a spruce near Winne and Cooke. Stayed until 1304 when if flew south and landed in the top of a spruce near Cooke and Highland after trying for an ECDO. Within less than a minute, it flew towards a spruce near me where I heard "cheep" calls from a HOFI - I also saw a second small raptor go after it, very likely the SSHA. the MERL missed, circled, and landed in a spruce on the east side of Cooke. At 1307 if flew west and landed in the top of a spruce ca 60-80 m west of Cooke. It remained perched there until 1312, when if flew back to the top of the spruce very near the corner of Cooke and Highland (also its second perch while I observed it). Soon a single BBMA joined it and harassed it, perching nearby and several times fluttering right above it within a meter or two. At 1313, a HOFI which had been apparently hiding in the same spruce flushed with sweet "cheep" calls and flew east - the MERL immediately took off in pursuit and was closing in when I lost sight of them both behind a spruce. Above: Path of the MERL and suspected path of the SSHA during this observation period, with observed perches numbered consecutively. Map drawn in the field; key and color-coding added later. Estimate of 200 meters from Highland to Winne was surprisingly accurate.

Media notes: Merlin adult female fling away from established tall oak tree high point and heading over the open Boulevard, perhaps to hunt or to locate the male bird.
Observation Details: Heard ‘Killdeer’ distress call and went out to Boulevard and saw an adult male Merlin going south and thought it was chasing a Killdeer, this about at 4:15 pm.  At this point, I actually pondered why this bird, likely the same one as seen earlier this week, was still around, especially with the warm weather passing through, so went outside looking for bird.  Ultimately saw the Merlin flying north so went that direction and ended up finding a female at top of an Oak half a block north of my place!  Constant calling heard, female calmly sits at top of tree and when she sees the male approaching, she gives a higher pitched call, sound like a wounded Killdeer.  The courtship flight, done by both male and female (but mostly by male) was a largely horizontal circling with fluttering wings, such that it looked like a Monk Parakeet in flight.  Twice saw the male land on top of the female and copulate (but only for 1 second, then 2 seconds the second time) - this was the first documented Illinois Merlin copulation!  Saw male bring in prey item (mouse or small bird), landed in conifer and plucked it a short time and left without it, almost like it was left somewhere on the branch for female to get.  Note, this Merlin was on territory here with a female since at least April 3rd, which led to Illinois first documented nest.  See eBird report here for full details:  https://ebird.org/view/checklist/S36878364.

Observation Details: Very dark Merlin (almost appeared jet black in low light and snow).  Much more dark coloration than light on breast. Same color on the back of head into the nape and into the back of the bird, no color change into primaries.  Short supercilium limited to just above the eye, dark cheek blended into malar giving appearance of no are hardly noticeable malar stripe.  Distinct, asymmetrical fish hook like shape to dark portions of undertail coverts.  Top of retrices appeared almost completely black, lacking any noticeable white or gray banding. Single whitish band on underside of retrices, separated from terminal white band with  a wide black subterminal band. Can provide reference documents used if needed.

Locality: Sevenmile Creek--Prickly Pear Land Trust (restricted access)
Observation Details: First observation at 0909. 1 counted on property. Interesting observation. A couple of BBMA were squawking and making a ruckus along the creek in reach 2. When I saw the birds they were in pursuit of a small raptor that was heading directly towards me. The BBMA peeled off and the MERL flew less than two meters over my head wheeled around and came straight back and perched in a burned alder approximately 6-7 meters away. It sat for approximately 20 seconds looking me over and then headed off upstream where the BBMA resumed their persecution. I saw it twice more - once while the BBMA were harrassing it, and again moments later sitting quietly in a nearby alder. Detections (number 15-minute intervals in which the species was detected): 1 on property.

Observation Details: Rare winter bird on MDI.  Immature  found along Knox Road. Initially on telephone wire then a truck disturbed it to a tree. This bird has an inconspicuous mustache  and overall brown plumage suggesting it is possibly an immature female.  Yellow cere, commisure and eye-ring offset beautifully the white supraorbital ridge, supercillium, malar and belly. Upperparts are streaked with white spotting on the flanks. The tail is banded white and brown with a distinctive broad white band on the tip. Pointed checkered underwings.

Media notes: Merlin || Chestnut Hill Reservoir, Brighton MA
Observation Details: Swooped up onto the top of a white oak tree in the parking area for the ice rink. As soon as I got binos on the bird I could see it was clutching a passerine prey; a House sparrow I think ... by the time I got the my scope set up the prey had been significantly torn apart. Over the next 30 minutes or so the Merlin devoured the entire sparrow; not a speck was left. It's possible that this bird has been here for some time this winter; while walking down Chestnut Hill Avenue in January at dusk I saw a small raptor dart overhead, which I presumed to be a Merlin but was never remotely sure. Locally rare, only 3 other records in eBird (Bouchard 3.29.11, Garvey & Trimble 12.4.08, Merrill 10.20.05).

Some quiet vocalization. Two were near each other in some snags, & three were sitting together on some dead branches...see photos. It looks like the male is still handing off food at the original tree at the back perimeter of the area. They are now hanging out way off to the right of the original area (nest site) - now parallel with the handoff tree probably about 500 feet away. The male, female, and 3 immatures were all present and accounted for... There was some vocalization, and three birds flew into the handoff tree. One ended up eating a meal. All information has been submitted to Donald Nixon for his PA Merlin's study. See checklists of 6/25, 7/4, & 7/7/23. *This is not the exact location.

Upon arrival the male and female adults were in trees about 40 yards apart. The female called for food several times, the male did not move. After several calls from the female she flew to where the male was and shagged him off his roost. The male was gone, apparently hunting, for about 30 minutes returning with prey. The two exchanged the caught bird and the female flew off to a tree and removed most of its feathers. The female then flew to the nest tree with it.
Photos to come. All 5 perching in dead pines. Both parents bringing in food (looked like HOFI) to three young! Wicked.

Merlin chick was found on the ground, calling incessantly, and seen running about on a few down trees. This was the closest I have ever come to a chick,  who might be fledged or had  fallen out of the nest?  Unclear but very cool expereince. No adults were in sight nor did  we see them feeding the chick?

Three juveniles perched in close proximity to one another, not far from where a nest was suspected but never located. Intermittently vocalizing; their calls were similar to that of the adults except lower volume and slightly more "whiney." One adult flew in with prey in  its talons, and there was a burst of frenzied activity as the young birds reacted by flying closer and calling more urgently. One fledgling quickly received the prey item (bird) and moved away to eat it, leaving the remaining fledglings perched and waiting. We didn't wait to observe further feedings.
Photos to come. All 5 perching in dead pines. Both parents bringing in food (looked like HOFI) to three young! Wicked.

On top of the power pole directly across Peck Ave. from the MB Botanical Garden.    Eating what looks to be a small bird.     I watched it long enough to see it fly away from me over Begg Field and the back was somewhat darkish.     Small Falcon with weak "mustache" and light plumage on face which makes me believe this could be a "Prairie" Merlin.   The last photo with an entrail in the mouth seems to show white undertail coverts, which also would be a "Prairie."  Other photos seem to show darker gray wings and the breast striping seems heavy, so perhaps a "Taiga" Merlin.   Legs are covered with tawny plumage, which I have seen on both "Prairie" and "Taiga" in photos in books and online.

I would also say its a male from my checked illustrations. Not dark enough to be a Pacific (Black) type and not light enough to be a Prairie type. Missed seeing it take off as I got sidetracked but the massive Geese fly over

**Uncommon but expected, though definitely more scarce in winter as compared to migration. Our latest record here and the first for December. My greatest experience with a Merlin ever at the Landing, and one of my best overall in a long time. I was walking down to the waterfront to scope the river a little, but before I got to Clubhouse Dr, I peered up at the Olive-sided branch and, to my surprise, saw a fairly large bird perched. This branch always gets great species and even though this bird was horribly backlit, I had a feeling it was a goodie. Indeed, a moment later I realized it was a Merlin, which got me particularly excited since non-flyover MERL here are very infrequent and this would be the first not at the beach. Moments later, I saw this bird was eating a small passerine (photos reveal it to look like Titmouse) and I got to enjoy some great views of this bird as it preened and fed. The bird remained on this perch for the next two hours (!!), eventually offering great, non-backlit views. I got to watch it from various angles (including directly underneath!) and in various lighting, offering me my best views of a Merlin in ages! A fantastic bird on a pretty darn good day! Photos to come (and I’d add video too if I could)

I heard one vocalizing and saw it flying in circles over a tree. It called a couple more times and then it flew towards the southwest, meandering a little, circling a little and then continuing on. Very shortly thereafter, one landed on a power stanchion and there's no way it could have been the same bird because the bird flying towards the southwest absolutely could not have turned and come back that far, that fast. Later as I was photographing the one perched on the stanchion, the second one came back and they both actually had a little interaction right above me as I was standing there with my mouth hanging open. The recording of a brief vocalization from that is attached to this report. First time for 2 in June; second consecutive year for Summit County Summer Breeding Bird Census.

Sought opinions of respected hawk birders, Alex Lamoreaux and Luke Tiller, who concurred with Prairie Merlin as subspecies. Also Ted Floyd thought Prairie. Michael Retter notes inter grades abound. Eric Carpenter and J. LeClaire were OK with validating as Prairie but noted facial markings perhaps too dark for Prairie. So given conflicting opinions elected for most accurate reporting of simply Merlin. Appreciate feedback given.

Saw three individuals in this location for the first time. The third one may be the child of the pair I've seen here on multiple occasions. I first heard their unique klee-klee-klee call, then saw them chasing each other through the air out in the open. I recognized the spotted undersides of the pointed wings and breast. They landed in the dead branches of a nearby tree and continued to call to each other. They left and came back multiple times over the course of the hour, giving me opportunities for photos both perched and in flight.

Heard from KT Lagoon; followed to golf course where the pair likely have a nest near Blaine and Kearney. Recorded extensive alarm calling with American Crows from the club house area. The two Merlins and 10-20 crows were all in the tree tops giving alarm calls for 10 minutes at least. There may have been an unseen eagle or hawk in a tree, which the crows appeared to swoop at. The Merlins made no attempts to dive on or attack anyone; they just called from tree tops.

Locality: Stringline Rd. And 1900 N, Eden, Utah, US (41.293, -111.807)
Observation Details: Very dark Merlin (almost appeared jet black in low light and snow).  Much more dark coloration than light on breast. Same color on the back of head into the nape and into the back of the bird, no color change into primaries.  Short supercilium limited to just above the eye, dark cheek blended into malar giving appearance of no are hardly noticeable malar stripe.  Distinct, asymmetrical fish hook like shape to dark portions of undertail coverts.  Top of retrices appeared almost completely black, lacking any noticeable white or gray banding. Single whitish band on underside of retrices, separated from terminal white band with  a wide black subterminal band. Can provide reference documents used if needed.

I spent considerable time with this Merlin.  It would make runs over the marsh to harass a Northern Harrier, then return to one of two nearby trees.  Unfortunately, when it was in the open it was up sun, and when I could get up sun from it, it was hidden in the tree (last photo).  At one point I thought it was casting a pellet (first photo), but it looks to me it was a small bone, perhaps from a recent meal.  In the fourth photo, I believe it has the Harrier in an inverted position.
